Vladimir Poutine and the Risk of a Third World War
SAN FRANCISCO – Russia's invasion of Ukraine on February 24 marked the beginning of a third world war that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
The invasion was preceded by a long meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the start of the Chinese New Year celebrations and the Winter Olympics in Beijing.
At the end of this meeting, the two men published a 5,000-word document, carefully drafted, announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any treaty and certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seems to have given Putin free rein to invade and go to war against Ukraine.
He must be very confident and consider it a mere formality his confirmation as China's leader for life later this year.
After gathering all power under his control, Xi carefully prepared the scenario in which he will rise to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After obtaining Xi's support, Putin has embarked on realizing the dream of his life with incredible brutality.
As he approaches 70 years old, Putin believes that if he wants to impose his mark on Russian history, it is now or never.
But his conception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar they can follow blindly.
This is precisely the opposite of a democratic society - and it is a vision that distorts the "soul" of Russia, emotional to the point of sensibility.
As a child, I met many Russian soldiers when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I learned that they were ready to share their last piece of bread with you if you asked them.
Later, in the early 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I established a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively contributed to the dissolution of the Soviet empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, the dissolution had already begun.
I founded a foundation in Russia, then did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner authorized to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989, just before the Tian'anmen Square massacre).
I do not know Putin personally, but I have observed his rise to power very closely, being aware of his cruelty.
He reduced Grozny, the capital of Chechnya, to ruins. And he threatens to do the same with the Ukrainian capital, Kyiv.
Putin was once a cunning KGB operator, but it seems he has changed recently.
Having developed a fixed idea, it seems he has lost touch with reality.
He certainly misread the situation in Ukraine.
He expected that Ukrainian Russian speakers would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but they turned out to be in precisely the same position as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
The Ukrainians have set up an incredibly courageous resistance against an opponent that nothing seems able to stop.
In July 2021, Putin published a long essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are really one people and that Ukrainians have been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
But in the second part, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have been more cautious.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the 'Euromaidan demonstrations in 2014.
The events of 2014 plunged him into a deep rage.
But the Russian army did poorly when ordered to attack its Ukrainian brothers.
The deep-seated corruption in defense contract allocation has also played a significant role in its inadequate results.
However, rather than blaming himself, Putin seems to have literally lost his mind.
He has decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and appears to be acting without encountering any resistance whatsoever.
He sends the entire Russian army into battle and disregards all rules of war, including indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals have been hit, and the power grid that supplies the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has been damaged.
In Mariupol under siege, 400,000 people have been without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia could well be losing the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to acquire Russian-made MiG fighters that Ukrainian pilots know how to fly.
This could make all the difference.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has already done wonders by succeeding in reinforcing the determination and unity of the EU.
Pendant ce temps, Xi semble avoir réalisé que Poutine fait cavalier seul.
Le 8 mars, un jour après que le ministre chinois des Affaires étrangères Wang Yi a insisté pour que l'amitié entre la Chine et la Russie reste « solide », Xi a appelé le président français Emmanuel Macron et le chancelier allemand Olaf Scholz pour dire qu'il soutenait leurs efforts de rétablissement de la paix.
Il a souhaité exprimer un maximum de retenue dans la guerre pour éviter une crise humanitaire.
Il est loin d'être certain que Poutine accédaît aux souhaits de Xi.
Nous ne pouvons qu'espérer que Poutine et Xi seront destitués avant qu'ils ne détruisent notre civilisation.
